  "expected_detection": {
    "should_alert_on": "attack_sequence",
    "should_not_alert_on": "benign_similar",
    "key_fields": [
      "process.executable",
      "process.parent.name",
      "user.name",
      "user.domain",
      "winlog.event_data.GrantedAccess",
      "winlog.event_data.TargetImage"
    ],
    "notes": "Detection anchors: (1) process.executable matching C:\\ProgramData\\* spawning privileged children as SYSTEM while parent ran as domain user — user context flip is the strongest signal; (2) GrantedAccess 0x1fffff against winlogon.exe or lsass.exe from a non-system binary in a writable directory; (3) child process user.domain = 'NT AUTHORITY' where parent user.domain = 'CORP' in the same process tree. Benign differentiation: GrantedAccess values below 0x1000 from winlogon.exe and processes with signed parents from System32 should be excluded. False positives: some EDR agents and AV products open privileged processes with broad access masks — tune by excluding known-signed executables in System32/Program Files."
  },
